    quizletSetId: '1122717715',
    content: `Organic Molecules → Biochemistry • Study of chemical composition and reactions occurring in living matter • Inorganic compounds • Do not contain carbon • Exceptions - CO 2 ​ , CO, bicarbonates • Water is the most abundant and important inorganic material, making up to 60% - 80% of all cells and 2/3 body weight. → Carbon Compounds • Most compounds that contain carbon are called organic. • Most inorganic compounds do not contain carbon atoms. • Macromolecules are large organic molecules. → Energy Currency • Adenosine Triphosphate (ATP) stores and releases energy during cell processes, enabling organisms to function. → Organic Compounds • Contain the element carbon, hydrogen and oxygen. • Carbon is found in things that are or once living. • Organic compounds are composed of hundreds to thousands of individual molecules. • The single molecules in a polymer are called monomers. • The long molecules formed by repeating patterns of monomers are called polymers. → Macromolecules • Large organic molecules • Also called polymers • Made up of smaller "building blocks" called monomers. • 4 types of organic compounds or macromolecules: 1. Carbohydrates 2. Lipids 3. Proteins 4. Nucleic acids (DNA and RNA) • Essential to maintaining life processes: cell function, storage, energy, homeostasis and genetic information. → Carbohydrates (short term energy storage) • Made up of sugars and starches • Contain carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen (in a 1:2:1 ratio) • Primary source of energy for cells (used to make ATP) • Can serve as structural materials in organisms • Starches → short-term energy storage • Cellulose → structural support in plants • Sucrose → common sugar (a type of carbohydrate polymer) • Glucose → main monomer (building block) for carbohydrates → Types of Carbohydrates • Carbohydrates are classified according to size. • One sugar is a monosaccharide (monomer). • Two sugars make a disaccharide. • Many sugar molecules linked together form a polysaccharide (polymer). • Monosaccharide: one sugar unit • Examples: • glucose (C 6 ​ H 1 ​ 2 ​ O 6 ​ blood sugar) • deoxyribose • ribose • galactose (milk sugar) • fructose (honey) • Provide cells with energy. • Disaccharide: two sugar units • Example: sucrose → glucose + fructose • Maltose is two glucose molecules; forms in digestive tract of humans during starch digestion. • Polysaccharide: many sugar units (short term energy storage) • Examples: • starch (bread, potatoes) • glycogen (beef muscle) • cellulose (lettuce, corn) • chitin (exoskeletons) • Store energy and provide structural support • Starch is a straight chain of glucose molecules with side branches. → Lipids (long term energy storage) • General term for compounds which are not soluble in water (nonpolar molecules). • Lipids are soluble in hydrophobic solvents. • Remember: "it stores the most energy" • The three types of lipids are fats, oils, and waxes. • Contain carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen • Typically contain two monomers → glycerol and fatty acids. • 5 functions of lipids: 1. Long term energy storage (fat) 2. Protection against heat loss (insulation) 3. Protection against water loss & germs (oils & waxes) 4. Chemical messengers (hormones & steroids) 5. Major component of membranes (phospholipids → found in cell membranes) • Fatty acids • Fatty acids can be saturated or unsaturated → Proteins • Amino acids • Proteins are made up of monomers called amino acids. The sequence of amino acids determines a proteins shape and function. • Proteins are the building materials for the body. • Hair, skin, muscles, and organs are made mostly of proteins. • Composed of carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, and nitrogen • Function of proteins • The building blocks of proteins are amino acids (monomers). • Serve as enzymes which control rate of reactions and regulate cell processes. → Nucleic Acids (DNA, RNA) • Heredity - DNA tells you who you are • A nucleic acid is a large and complex molecule that stores and transports information. • Formed from polymers of nucleotides → molecules composed of a phosphate group, a five-carbon sugar, and a nitrogenous base. • There are 5 different nitrogenous bases: 1. Adenine 2. Guanine 3. Cytosine 4. Thymine 5. Uracil • The nucleic acid deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) contains genetic information for cell activities. • Ribonucleic acid (RNA) molecules play many key roles in building of proteins. Structure: • DNA (Deoxyribonucleic Acid): • Double-stranded (forms a double helix) • Sugar is deoxyribose • Contains the nitrogen bases A, T, C, and G (adenine, thymine, cytosine, guanine) • RNA (Ribonucleic Acid): • Single-stranded • Sugar is ribose • Contains A, U, C, and G — uracil (U) replaces thymine Function: • DNA stores the genetic blueprint — it holds the instructions for making proteins. • RNA helps carry out those instructions: • mRNA (messenger RNA) copies the DNA code, • tRNA (transfer RNA) brings amino acids to the ribosome, and • rRNA (ribosomal RNA) helps build the protein.`,
