    quizletSetId: '1122718833',
    content: `Enzymes → What Are Enzymes? • Enzymes are biological catalysts — specialized proteins that speed up chemical reactions inside living organisms without being consumed or permanently changed. • Each enzyme has a unique structure determined by the specific order of its amino acids, which fold into a precise 3D shape. • This shape determines which substrate(s) the enzyme acts on — making enzymes highly specific. • Most enzyme names end with the suffix “-ase”, which often indicates their substrate: • Sucrase → breaks down sucrose • Lactase → breaks down lactose • Maltase → breaks down maltose • Enzymes are reusable and can catalyze reactions repeatedly as long as conditions remain favorable. → How Do Enzymes Work? • Enzymes lower the activation energy of reactions — the minimum energy needed for reactants to react. • They do this by weakening existing bonds in the substrate, allowing reactions to occur faster and with less energy input. → Enzyme-Substrate Complex • The substrate is the reactant that an enzyme acts upon. • When the substrate binds to the enzyme’s active site, it forms a temporary enzyme-substrate complex, where the reaction occurs. → Active Site & Induced Fit • The active site is the small, specifically shaped region on an enzyme that fits the substrate. • According to the induced fit model, the enzyme slightly changes its shape when the substrate binds, improving the fit and the reaction efficiency. • This flexibility helps explain how enzymes can adapt to slightly different substrates while still maintaining specificity. → Factors Affecting Enzyme Activity 1. Temperature • Increasing temperature generally increases reaction rate because molecules move faster and collide more often. • The reaction reaches its fastest point at the optimum temperature (around 37°C in humans). • Beyond this, enzymes denature — their shape changes and the active site no longer fits the substrate. 2. pH • Each enzyme has an optimum pH, usually around 6–8 for most human enzymes. • Extreme pH values alter the enzyme’s shape, leading to denaturation and loss of function. 3. Substrate and Enzyme Concentration • Increasing either can speed up reactions, but only until all active sites are occupied (enzyme saturation). 4. Ionic Concentration (Salinity) • High or low salt levels can interfere with the ionic bonds maintaining enzyme structure, affecting activity. → Catalysts vs. Enzymes • A catalyst is any substance that speeds up a chemical reaction without being changed itself. • Enzymes are biological catalysts — specialized for reactions in living cells. Example: • Hydrogen peroxide naturally breaks down into water and oxygen: • 2H 2 ​ O 2 ​ → 2H 2 ​ O + O 2 ​ • The enzyme catalase (peroxidase) accelerates this process, producing visible bubbling (oxygen gas). → Importance of Shape (Lock and Key Theory) • The enzyme’s shape determines which substrate it can bind to — similar to how a key fits a specific lock. • If the enzyme denatures (due to heat or pH), the active site shape changes, preventing substrate binding. → Industrial and Biological Uses of Enzymes 1. Biological Washing Powders • Contain proteases and other enzymes that break down stains (like proteins and fats) into smaller, water-soluble pieces. • Allow washing at lower temperatures, saving energy. 2. Food Industry • Pectinase: breaks down cell wall substances in fruit to increase juice yield. • Lactase: breaks down lactose into glucose and galactose — used to make lactose-free milk. 3. Seed Germination • Enzymes help break down stored food (like starch and proteins) into smaller molecules that the growing embryo can use. Acids, Bases, and pH → Acid • A substance that releases hydrogen ions (H + ) when dissolved in water. → Base • A substance that releases hydroxide ions (OH − ) when dissolved in water. → pH Scale • Measures the concentration of hydrogen ions (H + ) in a solution. • pH 7: Neutral (e.g., pure water) • pH < 7: Acidic (higher H + concentration) • pH > 7: Basic or Alkaline (lower H + concentration) → Neutralization • When an acid reacts with a base, the products are a salt and water: • Acid + Base → Salt + Water`,
