    quizletSetId: '1120255848',
    content: `The Cell Definition of a Cell • A cell is the smallest unit of life capable of performing all life functions. • Examples: Amoeba proteus, bacteria, nerve cell, plant stem cell, red blood cell. Types of Cells There are two main types of cells: Prokaryotic Cells • Simple cells with no nucleus and no membrane-bound organelles. • DNA floats freely in the cytoplasm. • Usually unicellular organisms like bacteria. • Example: Lactobacillus acidophilus (found in yogurt) Key features: • Few internal structures • Surrounded by a plasma membrane • Very small and visible only under high magnification Eukaryotic Cells • Complex cells that have a true nucleus and membrane-bound organelles. • Found in plants, animals, fungi, and protists. • Much larger and more organized than prokaryotic cells. Animal vs. Plant Cells Feature Animal Cell Plant Cell Shape Round or irregular Rectangular Cell Wall None Present (for structure/support) Chloroplasts Absent Present (for photosynthesis) Vacuoles Small, temporary Large central vacuole Example Muscle cell, nerve cell Leaf cell, root cell Centrioles Present Absent Flagella/Cilia May be present Rare (some algae) Cell Organelles — “The Working Parts of the Cell” Surrounding the Cell Cell Membrane (Plasma Membrane) • The outer boundary of the cell. • Controls what enters and leaves — “the gatekeeper.” • Made of a phospholipid bilayer (Fluid Mosaic Model → Patterns). • Maintains homeostasis by keeping conditions stable inside the cell. Cell Wall • Found in plants, bacteria, and fungi (not animals). • Provides support, protection, and shape. • Made of cellulose (the same fiber used in cotton and paper). Inside the Cell Nucleus • The control center of the cell. • Contains DNA, which stores genetic instructions. • Enclosed by the nuclear membrane. Chromosomes • Structures made of DNA inside the nucleus. • Carry genes that determine traits. Nucleolus • Found inside the nucleus. • Makes RNA and ribosomes, which are needed for protein synthesis. Cytoplasm • The gel-like fluid filling the cell. • Holds all organelles in place. • Site of many chemical reactions. Endoplasmic Reticulum (ER) • Transports materials within the cell. • Smooth ER: No ribosomes, makes lipids. • Rough ER: Has ribosomes, helps make proteins. Ribosomes • Protein factories of the cell. • Found floating in cytoplasm or attached to rough ER. • Site of protein synthesis. Mitochondria • The powerhouse of the cell. • Converts glucose into energy (ATP) through chemical reactions. • Cells that need more energy (like muscle cells) have many mitochondria. Golgi Apparatus (aka Golgi Bodies/Golgi Complex) • The cell’s packaging and shipping center. • Modifies, sorts, and packages proteins for transport inside or outside the cell. Lysosomes • The cell’s digestive system. • Breaks down wastes, old cell parts, and large molecules. • If they burst, the cell can be destroyed. Vacuoles • Storage sacs for food, water, or waste. • Plant cells have one large central vacuole for storing water and maintaining shape. • Animal cells have smaller vacuoles. Chloroplasts • Found in plant cells only. • Site of photosynthesis — converts sunlight into chemical energy. • Contains green pigment chlorophyll. Centrioles • Found in animal cells (NOT in plant cells) • Paired cylinder-shaped structures located near the nucleus • Help organize cell division by forming spindle fibers that separate chromosomes • Play a key role in mitosis and meiosis Flagella • Long, whip-like structures that extend from the cell surface • Used for cell movement and locomotion • Example: Sperm cells use a flagellum to swim • Longer than cilia, and cells usually have only one or a few flagella Cilia • Short, hair-like structures covering the cell surface • Move in coordinated wave-like motions • Used for movement or moving materials across the cell surface • Example: Cilia in your respiratory tract sweep mucus and debris out of your lungs • Cells typically have many cilia Cell Theory 1. All living things are made of cells. 2. The cell is the basic unit of life. 3. All cells come from pre-existing cells. Key Scientists: • Matthias Schleiden: All plants are made of cells. • Theodor Schwann: All animals are made of cells. • Robert Hooke: Named “cells” after observing cork under a simple microscope. • Anton van Leeuwenhoek: First to observe living cells using a compound microscope.`,
