    quizletSetId: '1111521452',
    content: `Cellular Transport The Cell Membrane A. Overview • All cells have a cell membrane. • Functions: 1. Controls what enters and exits the cell to maintain homeostasis (internal balance). 2. Provides protection and structural support. Structure • Lipid Bilayer: two layers of phospholipids • Phosphate head: polar → hydrophilic (“water-loving”) • Fatty acid tails: nonpolar → hydrophobic (“water-fearing”) • Heads face outward (toward water); tails face inward (away from water) • Proteins: embedded in membrane; act as transport channels, receptors, or structural supports. • Carbohydrates: attached to lipids or proteins → act as cell markers for identification. • Cholesterol: stabilizes the membrane and keeps it flexible. Fluid Mosaic Model • “Fluid” → phospholipids and proteins move freely within the layer. • “Mosaic” → made of many different molecules (lipids, proteins, carbs). • Describes the dynamic, flexible nature of the membrane. Selective Permeability • The membrane has pores (holes) that allow only certain molecules through. • Selectively permeable: some molecules pass freely, others are blocked. • The structure (lipid bilayer + proteins) helps determine what enters and exits. Types of Cellular Transport Type Energy Used? Movement Direction Examples Passive Transport ❌ No High → Low concentration Diffusion, Facilitated Diffusion, Osmosis Active Transport ✅ Yes Low → High concentration Protein Pumps, Endocytosis, Exocytosis Passive Transport Movement of molecules without energy (down the concentration gradient). 1. Diffusion • Random movement of molecules from high → low concentration. • Continues until equilibrium (evenly spaced). • Molecules still move at equilibrium but remain evenly distributed. • Moves small, nonpolar molecules like O 2 ​ , CO 2 ​ , and lipids. 2. Facilitated Diffusion • Diffusion of specific particles through transport proteins. • Still passive (no energy needed). • Transport proteins are specific — only allow certain molecules. • Moves larger or charged molecules (e.g., glucose, ions). Two Types of Transport Proteins: 1. Channel proteins: form open pores for molecules to pass through. 2. Carrier proteins: change shape to move molecules across. 3. Osmosis • Diffusion of water through a selectively permeable membrane. • Water moves from high water (low solute) → low water (high solute). • Water moves freely through pores or aquaporins. • Solute particles (like salt or sugar) are too large to move through the membrane. Effects of Osmosis on Cells Type of Solution Definition Water Movement Effect on Cell Hypotonic Solution has low solute, high water outside the cell Water moves into the cell Cell swells and may burst (cytolysis) Hypertonic Solution has high solute, low water outside the cell Water moves out of the cell Cell shrinks (plasmolysis) Isotonic Solute concentration equal inside and outside Water moves equally both directions Cell remains the same size (dynamic equilibrium) Active Transport Requires energy (ATP) to move materials against the concentration gradient (Low → High). 1. Protein Pumps • Transport proteins that require ATP to move molecules across the membrane. • Example: Sodium-Potassium Pump • Pumps Na + out and K + in. • Important for nerve function and maintaining membrane potential. • Protein changes shape during transport (requires energy). 2. Endocytosis • Takes materials into the cell by folding the membrane inward. • Uses energy (ATP). • The membrane surrounds the material and forms a vacuole. Two Main Types: 1. Phagocytosis (“cell eating”) – takes in solids (e.g., how white blood cells engulf bacteria). 2. Pinocytosis (“cell drinking”) – takes in liquids. 3. Exocytosis • Forces materials out of the cell in bulk. • A vesicle containing the material fuses with the cell membrane. • The cell changes shape to release contents → requires energy. • Examples: releasing hormones, digestive enzymes, or wastes. Osmotic Pressure in Living Organisms • Bacteria and plants have cell walls that prevent them from bursting. • Water pressure against the cell wall is called turgor pressure. • Protists (like paramecium) use contractile vacuoles to pump out excess water → prevents over-expansion. • Saltwater fish pump salt out through specialized gills to avoid dehydration. • Animal cells are bathed in isotonic blood plasma; • Kidneys regulate salt and water to maintain balance. Summary Review Table Process Type Energy Needed? Direction (Concentration) Example / Function Diffusion Passive ❌ No High → Low O₂, CO₂ across membrane Facilitated Diffusion Passive ❌ No High → Low Glucose, ions via proteins Osmosis Passive ❌ No High → Low (water) Water balance Protein Pump Active ✅ Yes Low → High Na⁺/K⁺ Pump in nerves Endocytosis Active ✅ Yes Into cell White blood cell engulfing bacteria Exocytosis Active ✅ Yes Out of cell Hormones or wastes released`,
