    quizletSetId: '1120258987',
    content: `Cell Energy ATP (Adenosine Triphosphate) • ATP is the cell’s primary energy carrier, produced mainly in mitochondria during cellular respiration. • Energy is stored in the bond between ATP’s last two phosphate groups. • Energy release: ATP → ADP + P releases energy used by the cell. • ATP formation: ADP + P → ATP using energy harvested from glucose (and oxygen when aerobic). Photosynthesis (and why autotrophs matter) • Definition: Conversion of light energy into chemical energy (glucose) by plants, algae, and some bacteria. • Location: Chloroplasts; chlorophyll absorbs light. • Inputs: Sunlight, CO 2 ​ (enters through stomata), H 2 ​ O. • Outputs: Glucose (used, stored as starch, or built into tissue) and O 2 ​ (released). • Balanced equation: • 6CO 2 ​ + 6H 2 ​ O + light → C 6 ​ H 1 ​ 2 ​ O 6 ​ + 6O 2 ​ • Importance of autotrophs: They produce the oxygen we breathe and the organic molecules (glucose) that form the base of nearly all food chains — without autotrophs most life on Earth could not survive. Cellular Respiration • Definition: Process in which cells break down glucose to produce ATP. • Occurs in: Mitochondria (in eukaryotes), in all living cells. • With or without oxygen: Can be aerobic (with O₂) or anaerobic (without O₂). • Balanced equation (aerobic): • C 6 ​ H 1 ​ 2 ​ O 6 ​ + 6O 2 ​ → 6CO 2 ​ + 6H 2 ​ O + ATP • Role: Harvests chemical energy from glucose and converts it to ATP for cellular work. Photosynthesis vs Cellular Respiration Aspect Photosynthesis Cellular Respiration Purpose Make glucose (store energy) Make ATP (useable energy) Occurs in Chloroplasts (plants, algae) Mitochondria (all eukaryotic cells) Energy source Light energy Chemical energy in glucose Inputs CO₂, H₂O, light C₆H₁₂O₆, O₂ (aerobic) Outputs C₆H₁₂O₆, O₂ CO₂, H₂O, ATP Net effect Stores energy in sugar Releases energy from sugar Anaerobic vs Aerobic Feature Aerobic Respiration Anaerobic Respiration Oxygen required? Yes No ATP yield High (≈10× more than anaerobic) Low Typical products CO₂ + H₂O + lots of ATP Varies: alcohol + CO₂ (yeast) OR lactic acid (muscle) + small ATP Where common Most cells (mitochondria) When O₂ is scarce (muscle during intense exercise, microorganisms) Example processes Cellular respiration (glycolysis → Krebs → ETC) Alcohol fermentation, lactic acid fermentation Effects Efficient energy production Quick energy; byproducts can cause fatigue (lactic acid) or used in fermentation`,
