    quizletSetId: '1120243601',
    content: `Cell Division & Reproduction Basic Principles of Cell Division • All cells come from preexisting cells. • Cell division produces two daughter cells from one parent cell. • Daughter cells produced by mitosis are genetically identical to the parent cell. • Chromosomes are the carriers of genetic information. • Chromatin = long strands of DNA wrapped around proteins (histones). Why Cells Divide Cells must divide in order to: 1. Maintain a workable surface area–to–volume ratio so materials can move in and out efficiently. 2. Allow for growth, repair, and replacement of damaged or dead cells. Types of Reproduction Asexual Reproduction • Involves one parent, & produces genetically identical offspring • No genetic variation • Used by: Prokaryotes & Some eukaryotes Sexual Reproduction • Involves two parents and produces genetically unique offspring • Results in high genetic variation • Involves meiosis and fertilization Rate of Cell Division Cell division rate depends on: • Availability of nutrients, enzymes, and proteins • Proper environmental conditions Examples: • Bacteria: divide every ~20 minutes • Skin cells: divide every 18–22 hours Prokaryotic Cell Division (Asexual) Prokaryotes divide by binary fission: • DNA copies • Cell splits into two identical cells • No genetic variation Other asexual methods (some organisms): • Budding – unequal division, bud pinches off • Spore formation – protective structure formed for survival in harsh conditions All asexual reproduction results in clones. Eukaryotic Cell Division Eukaryotic cells divide using: • Mitosis → body cells (asexual reproduction) • Meiosis → sex cells (sexual reproduction) Process Purpose Result Mitosis Growth, repair 2 identical diploid (2n) cells Meiosis Sexual reproduction 4 genetically different haploid (n) cells The Cell Cycle The cell cycle has two major parts: 1. Interphase 2. Cell Division (Mitosis + Cytokinesis) Interphase (Longest Stage) This is when the cell grows and prepares for division. G1 Phase • Cell grows and makes proteins rapidly and organelles S Phase • DNA is replicated • Chromosomes duplicate into sister chromatids • Sister chromatids are connected by a centromere • DNA must be copied so each new cell gets a full, identical set of genes G2 Phase • Cell organizes and prepares for mitosis Mitosis (Nuclear Division) 1. Prophase • Chromosomes condense and become visible • Nuclear membrane breaks down • Centrioles move to opposite poles • Spindle fibers form 2. Metaphase • Chromosomes align at the equator (middle) • Spindle fibers attach to the centromeres 3. Anaphase • Sister chromatids separate • Spindle fibers pull them toward opposite poles 4. Telophase • Chromosomes arrive at opposite poles • Two new nuclei form • Chromosomes uncoil and become chromatin Cytokinesis • The cytoplasm divides • Results in two identical diploid daughter cells Cancer & Cell Division • Cancer is a disease of uncontrolled mitosis. • Occurs when cell cycle checkpoints fail. • A normal cell becomes a cancer cell due to DNA mutations. • Cancer cells: • Divide without control • Ignore normal stopping signals • Can become immortal (normal cells divide ~50 times, but cancer cells can divide forever) Tumors • A tumor is a mass of cancer cells. • Tumors cause angiogenesis (growth of new blood vessels). • At ~1 million cells, a tumor is around the size of a BB pellet. Types of Tumors • Benign – remains at original site • Malignant – spreads to other tissues (metastasis) via bloodstream or lymph Mitosis is critical to cancer research because cancer is uncontrolled mitosis. Meiosis (Sexual Reproduction) • Used to form gametes (sex cells) • Gametes must be haploid (n) and body cells are diploid (2n) • Two parents contribute a set of chromosomes each through gametes • Together they form a zygote (diploid) • Homologous chromosomes: control the same traits • Not necessarily identical genes Meiosis I (Reduction Division) Prophase I • Homologous chromosomes pair and crossing over occurs • Creates genetic variation Metaphase I • Homologous pairs line up randomly at the equator • Independent assortment increases variation Anaphase I • Homologous chromosomes separate • Sister chromatids remain together Telophase I • Two haploid cells form No interphase before Meiosis II Meiosis II • Functions just like mitosis • Sister chromatids separate • Results in four genetically different haploid cells Human Chromosomes • Humans have 46 chromosomes (23 pairs) • Autosomes = pairs 1–22 • Sex chromosomes = pair 23 • Female: XX • Male: XY • Each homologous pair contains: • One chromosome from each parent Mitosis vs. Meiosis Summary Feature Mitosis Meiosis Purpose Growth, repair Sexual reproduction Number of divisions 1 2 Daughter cells 2 4 Chromosome number Diploid (2n) Haploid (n) Genetic makeup Identical Different Chromosomal Mutations • Deletion – a piece of chromosome is lost • Inversion – piece breaks off and reinserts backward • Translocation – piece attaches to a different chromosome These mutations may cause genetic disorders. Karyotypes • A karyotype shows the number, size, and shape of chromosomes • Used to identify genetic disorders such as Down syndrome (Trisomy 21)`,
