    content: `DNA, RNA, and Proteins – The Molecules of Life Living organisms are built and controlled by DNA, which is used to make RNA, which is used to build proteins. Proteins determine the structure and function of cells and the traits of organisms. This flow of information is called the Central Dogma: DNA → RNA → Protein DNA (Deoxyribonucleic Acid) What DNA Does DNA is the genetic blueprint of life. It: • Controls all chemical activities inside cells • Determines what type of cell forms (muscle, nerve, blood, etc.) • Determines what type of organism develops (human, fish, plant, etc.) • Stores instructions for making proteins DNA is found in the nucleus of eukaryotic cells (prokaryotes have DNA but no nucleus). DNA Structure DNA is a polymer made of repeating units called nucleotides. Each nucleotide has three parts: 1. Phosphate group 2. Deoxyribose sugar 3. Nitrogen base The Four DNA Bases There are four nitrogen bases: • A = Adenine • T = Thymine • G = Guanine • C = Cytosine Complementary Base Pairing DNA follows strict pairing rules: • A pairs with T (2 hydrogen bonds) • C pairs with G (3 hydrogen bonds) This pairing allows DNA to: • Be copied accurately • Store information in its sequence of bases DNA Shape DNA has a double helix shape (twisted ladder). • The sides are made of alternating sugar and phosphate • The rungs are made of paired nitrogen bases (A–T and C–G) DNA’s structure was described by Watson and Crick, based on the work of Rosalind Franklin. DNA Replication DNA replication occurs before a cell divides so each new cell gets a complete copy of DNA. Purpose • Ensures all body cells have the same genetic information • Allows DNA to be passed to offspring Steps of Replication 1. Helicase unwinds and unzips the DNA by breaking hydrogen bonds. 2. Each original strand acts as a template. 3. DNA polymerase: • Adds complementary nucleotides (A–T, C–G) • Proofreads and fixes errors 4. DNA ligase bonds the nucleotides together. 5. Two identical DNA molecules are produced. Replication is extremely accurate — about 1 error per billion nucleotides. RNA (Ribonucleic Acid) RNA is used to carry and interpret DNA’s instructions to make proteins. How RNA differs from DNA DNA RNA Double-stranded Single-stranded Deoxyribose sugar Ribose sugar Uses thymine (T) Uses uracil (U) Stays in nucleus Can leave nucleus RNA base pairing • A pairs with U • C pairs with G Types of RNA Three types of RNA are involved in making proteins: Type Function mRNA (messenger) Carries instructions from DNA to ribosome rRNA (ribosomal) Forms the ribosome tRNA (transfer) Brings amino acids to ribosome Protein Synthesis Protein synthesis has two stages: 1. Transcription (DNA → RNA) 2. Translation (RNA → Protein Transcription (DNA → mRNA) Occurs in the nucleus. Steps 1. DNA unwinds in a gene region. 2. mRNA is built by pairing with the DNA template: • A → U • T → A • C → G • G → C 3. mRNA detaches and leaves the nucleus. 4. mRNA travels to a ribosome. The Genetic Code • Every 3 bases on mRNA is a codon • Each codon codes for one amino acid • There are 64 codons • 61 code for amino acids • 3 are stop signals • AUG is the start codon (codes for methionine) Translation (mRNA → Protein) Occurs at the ribosome in the cytoplasm. Steps 1. mRNA binds to the ribosome. 2. tRNA brings amino acids to the ribosome. 3. The anticodon on tRNA matches the codon on mRNA. 4. Amino acids are joined together to form a polypeptide. 5. The chain continues growing until a stop codon is reached. 6. The completed protein is released. Why Proteins Matter Proteins: • Build cell structures • Act as enzymes • Control chemical reactions • Determine traits DNA doesn’t do the work — proteins do. DNA just provides the instructions.`,
