    quizletSetId: '1132591011',
    content: `Mutations What Are Mutations? • Mutations are changes in the nucleotide sequence of DNA. • They can occur: • In somatic (body) cells → not inherited • In gametes (sperm or egg cells) → can be passed to offspring • Mutations are a major source of genetic variation in populations. Are Mutations Helpful or Harmful? • Mutations occur regularly and naturally during DNA replication. • Most mutations are neutral, meaning they have no noticeable effect. • Some mutations are harmful, causing diseases or disorders. • A small number are beneficial, improving survival or reproduction. • Mutagens (agents that cause mutations) include: • UV radiation • Chemicals • Viruses • Cells have DNA repair enzymes that fix many mutations before they cause damage. • Examples of mutation-related diseases: • Skin cancer (often caused by UV damage in somatic cells) • Leukemia (caused by mutations affecting blood cell production) Types of Mutations 1. Chromosome Mutations • Involve large-scale changes to chromosomes. • May include: • Changes in chromosome structure • Loss or gain of chromosome segments • Often affect many genes at once, making them more severe. Types of Chromosome Mutations Deletion • A segment of a chromosome breaks off and is lost. • Results in missing genes. Inversion • A chromosome segment breaks off, flips, and reattaches. • Gene order is reversed, which can disrupt gene function. Duplication • A segment of a chromosome is copied and repeated. • Results in extra gene copies. Translocation • A segment of one chromosome moves to a non-homologous chromosome. • Can disrupt genes or create abnormal gene regulation. Nondisjunction • Failure of chromosomes to separate properly during meiosis. • Causes gametes with too many or too few chromosomes. • Leads to genetic disorders caused by abnormal chromosome numbers. Examples of Nondisjunction Disorders • Down Syndrome: three copies of chromosome 21 (Trisomy 21) • Turner Syndrome: only one X chromosome (XO) • Klinefelter Syndrome: extra sex chromosome (XXY) 2. Gene Mutations • Changes in the nucleotide sequence of a single gene. • Usually affect one protein. • Caused by: • DNA replication errors • Chemicals • Radiation • Viruses Types of Gene Mutations Point Mutations • Change in one single nucleotide. • Often involves substitution (one base replaces another). • May be: • Neutral • Harmful • Rarely beneficial • Not always guaranteed to cause a disorder. Example: Sickle Cell Disease • Caused by a single nucleotide substitution in the hemoglobin gene. • Changes the shape of red blood cells, affecting oxygen transport. Frameshift Mutations • Caused by insertion or deletion of one or more nucleotides. • Shifts the reading frame of the gene. • Affects every codon after the mutation, usually resulting in a nonfunctional protein. • Almost always harmful. Example • Original sentence: The fat cat ate the wee rat • Frameshift (extra “a” added): The fat caa tat eth ewe era t • Meaning is lost, similar to how protein instructions are disrupted.`,
