      'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Hd3fA4dLFm5VXKlYJ9B7wFEODrlJ79r9/view?usp=sharing',
    quizletSetId: '1153446809',
    content: `Genetics - Gregor Johann Mendel (1822–1884) • Austrian monk known as the Father of Genetics • Studied inheritance using pea plants from 1856–1863 • Conducted experiments on about 28,000 plants • Discovered the basic laws of inheritance • His work was not recognized until the early 1900s Why Mendel Used Pea Plants • Have clear contrasting traits • Can self-pollinate or be cross-pollinated • Short generation time • Produce many offspring Particulate Inheritance Particulate Inheritance – the idea that traits are inherited as discrete “particles” passed from parents to offspring. Today we know these particles are: • Genes located on • Chromosomes made of • DNA Traits are passed intact between generations rather than blending permanently. Genetic Terminology Basic Terms • Trait – A characteristic that can be inherited (ex: flower color) • Heredity – Passing of traits from parents to offspring • Genetics – Study of heredity • Gene – Segment of DNA that controls a trait • Alleles – Different versions of the same gene Dominant vs Recessive • Dominant allele – Expressed when at least one copy is present (capital letter, e.g., R) • Recessive allele – Expressed only when two copies are present (lowercase letter, e.g., r) Genotype vs Phenotype • Genotype – Genetic makeup (RR, Rr, rr) • Phenotype – Physical appearance resulting from genotype (round or wrinkled) Homozygous vs Heterozygous • Homozygous – Two identical alleles (RR or rr) — “pure” • Heterozygous – Two different alleles (Rr) — “hybrid” Gametes & Fertilization • Gametes – Sex cells (sperm and egg); contain half the genetic information (haploid, n) • Fertilization – Fusion of gametes forming a diploid (2n) zygote Mendel’s Pea Plant Traits Examples of traits Mendel studied: • Seed shape – Round (R) / Wrinkled (r) • Seed color – Yellow (Y) / Green (y) • Pod shape – Smooth (S) / Wrinkled (s) • Pod color – Green (G) / Yellow (g) • Plant height – Tall (T) / Short (t) • Flower color – Purple (P) / White (p) Mendel’s Laws of Inheritance Law of Dominance When two different alleles are present, the dominant allele masks the recessive allele. Law of Segregation The two alleles for a trait separate during gamete formation (meiosis) so each gamete carries only one allele. Law of Independent Assortment Alleles for different traits separate independently during gamete formation. This explains how different traits can be inherited independently of one another. Generations in Genetic Crosses • P1 Generation (Parental Generation) – the original parents in a breeding experiment • F1 Generation (First Filial Generation) – the first generation of offspring from the P1 cross • F2 Generation (Second Filial Generation) – the offspring produced when individuals from the F1 generation reproduce Punnett Squares Used to predict offspring genotypes and phenotypes. Steps: 1. Identify dominant and recessive alleles. 2. Determine parent genotypes. 3. List gametes from each parent. 4. Fill in combinations. 5. Determine genotype and phenotype ratios. Types of Genetic Crosses Monohybrid Cross A genetic cross that examines one trait. Example: Rr × Rr Dihybrid Cross A genetic cross that examines two traits simultaneously. Example: RrYy × RrYy Number of Possible Gametes Formula: 2 n , where n = number of heterozygous gene pairs Examples: • RrYy → 2 2 = 4 gametes • AaBbCCDd → 2 3 = 8 gametes • 6 heterozygous pairs → 2 6 = 64 gametes Complex Patterns of Inheritance Incomplete Dominance Incomplete Dominance – a pattern of inheritance in which the heterozygous phenotype is intermediate between the two homozygous phenotypes. Example: • Red flower × White flower → Pink flower Codominance Codominance – a pattern of inheritance where both alleles are fully and simultaneously expressed in the heterozygous individual. Example: Human blood types Multiple Alleles Multiple Alleles – a trait controlled by more than two allele forms within a population. Example: ABO Blood Types Polygenic Inheritance Polygenic Inheritance – an inheritance pattern in which a trait is controlled by two or more genes. Characteristics: • Produces continuous variation • Results in a wide range of phenotypes Example: • Skin color Sex-Linked (X-Linked) Inheritance Sex-Linked Inheritance – inheritance of genes located on the sex chromosomes, usually the X chromosome. • Females (XX) must inherit two recessive alleles to express the trait • Males (XY) need only one recessive allele Example: Colorblindness Alleles: • X B – normal vision • X b – colorblind Genetic Disorders Autosomal Dominant Disorders Autosomal Dominant Inheritance – a disorder caused by a dominant allele on an autosome; only one copy is needed to produce the disease. Example: Huntington’s disease (causes holes in the brain where tissue has been broken down) Autosomal Recessive Disorders Autosomal Recessive Inheritance – a disorder that occurs only when two recessive alleles are inherited. Individuals with one allele are carriers. Examples: • Cystic Fibrosis (accumulation of thick mucus in lungs and digestive tract) • Tay-Sachs Disease (lack of an enzyme that breaks down lipids brain, fat builds up in brain) • Phenylketonuria (PKU) (lacks enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase, amino acid builds up) X-Linked Disorders X-Linked Disorders – genetic disorders caused by mutations on the X chromosome. These disorders are more common in males because males only have one X chromosome. Example: Hemophilia Codominant Genetic Disorder Sickle Cell Anemia • A disorder where red blood cells become curved (sickle-shaped) • Cells carry less oxygen, depriving tissues of oxygen • Homozygous individuals have the disease • Heterozygous individuals are carriers Genetic Testing Amniocentesis Amniocentesis – a medical procedure used to detect genetic or chromosomal disorders in a developing fetus. • A needle removes amniotic fluid from the uterus • The fluid contains fetal cells for genetic testing`,
