      'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1d08jAq2oXigoIQF6KI1zzaWkrkcTwlYK/view?usp=sharing',
    quizletSetId: '1153447126',
    content: `Pedigrees - What is a Pedigree? • A pedigree is a diagram or chart that shows the inheritance of a trait within a family across multiple generations. • It is essentially a family tree used in genetics to track how a specific trait, genetic disorder, or characteristic is passed from parents to offspring. • Geneticists and genetic counselors construct pedigrees by collecting information about family members and their health histories. • Pedigrees allow scientists to analyze patterns of inheritance, determine whether a trait is dominant or recessive, and estimate the probability that future children will inherit a particular genetic condition. Constructing a Pedigree Interpreting a Pedigree Chart When analyzing a pedigree, scientists look for patterns that reveal how a trait is inherited. 1. Determine whether the trait is autosomal or sex-linked • Autosomal traits are controlled by genes located on the autosomes (non-sex chromosomes). • Sex-linked traits are controlled by genes located on the sex chromosomes, usually the X chromosome. Key clues: • If males and females are affected in roughly equal numbers, the trait is likely autosomal. • If males are affected much more frequently than females, the trait is often X-linked, because males have only one X chromosome, so a single recessive allele will cause the disorder. 2. Determine whether the trait is dominant or recessive • Dominant traits • Only one copy of the allele is required for the trait to appear. • An affected individual usually has at least one affected parent. • The trait typically appears in every generation of the pedigree. • Recessive traits • Two copies of the recessive allele are required for the trait to appear. • Parents may be unaffected carriers (heterozygous) but still have affected children. • The trait may skip generations because carriers do not show the phenotype. Summary • Pedigrees are diagrams used to trace the inheritance of traits through multiple generations of a family. • They help scientists and doctors identify patterns of inheritance, such as autosomal vs. sex-linked and dominant vs. recessive traits. • Pedigrees are also used to estimate the probability that a child will inherit a genetic disorder, which is important in genetic counseling and medical research. Example Pedigrees`,
