    pdfUrl:
      'https://drive.google.com/file/d/1wks5VPwvrF4SNG1F8nyc1L9C5IXCTtw5/view?usp=sharing',
    quizletSetId: '1153449905',
    content: `Environmental Influences - An organism’s genotype is not the only factor responsible for its phenotype. Environmental conditions can affect how genes are expressed, causing organisms with the same genes to sometimes show different traits. The Arctic Fox The Arctic fox shows how temperature can influence fur color. • When the outside temperature is warm, the hair is produced with dark pigment. • When the temperature is cold, the hair is produced with little or no pigment, causing the fur to appear white. This change helps the fox adapt to seasonal environmental conditions. The Himalayan Rabbit The Himalayan rabbit has white fur on most of its body, but the ears, nose, feet, and tail are black. These body parts are usually colder than the rest of the rabbit’s body, which allows black pigment to form in those areas. Scientists conducted an experiment to determine how temperature affects fur color in Himalayan rabbits. Experiment Scientists shaved an area of hair on the back of each rabbit. An ice pack was placed over the shaved area on one rabbit. Black pigment is deposited in fur when the temperature falls below about 33°F. • When the shaved area was cooled with an ice pack, the fur grew back black. • When the shaved area was not cooled, the fur grew back white. This experiment showed that environmental temperature can influence gene expression and phenotype. Identical Twin Studies Identical twins have identical genes because they come from the same fertilized egg. They share the same DNA but do not have identical fingerprints. Identical twins also often have very similar brain-wave patterns and occur in about 1 out of every 250 births. A twin study is a type of genetic research used to determine the heritability of traits. Since identical twins have the same genotype, scientists believe that differences between them are mainly caused by environmental factors. The environment can shape personality, but genes may influence the kinds of environments people experience, seek out, or respond to. Since the early 1960s, several twin studies have reported that identical twins raised apart can still be very similar, suggesting that genetics plays a strong role in many human traits.`,
